article.description: Tamika Catchings, Deanna Jackson and the Indiana Fever have finally put together consecutive wins. Deanna Nolan and the Detroit Shock are coming apart.
article.headline: Fever finally win two straight
article.linkText: Catchings, Jackson notch 19 each in Fever win
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Some extra practice is starting to pay off
for Indiana Fever forward Deanna Jackson.

Jackson had a season-high 19 points, nearly triple the 7.0
scoring average she brought into the game, and teammate Tamika
Catchings also had 19 as the Fever defeated the Detroit Shock 85-73
Friday night.

"I've been doing some extra shooting, doing extra things trying
to get my shot down," said Jackson, 9-for-12 from the field.

Indiana hit a season-high nine 3-pointers on 14 attempts, and
also had season-bests with 37 assists and 54-percent shooting. The
Fever's point total was also six higher than its previous best.

The victory moved Indiana into first place in the Eastern
Conference, a half-game ahead of Charlotte.

"We stepped up big and hit open shots against the zone. We
moved the ball around a lot," Catchings said.

Jackson, whose previous high this season was 14 points, said the
crisp ball movement led to much easier shots.

"We worked the ball around and made the extra pass," she said.
"With a wide open jumper, it is easy to knock down the shot."

Deanna Nolan led Detroit with 20 points before being ejected in
the final minute. She picked up two technical fouls in the final
three minutes.

For the Shock, it was another poor defensive effort. Indiana
entered the game last in the league in shooting at 39 percent, but
found the going easy against Detroit.

"We're having a hard time being intense on the defensive end
right now," Nolan said. "We are not rotating very well on
defense.

"A lot of times we'll get the first rotation but miss the
second and it's leaving people open for easy shots."

Reserve Kelly Schumacher added 14 points for Indiana, which got
13 and a career-high seven assists from Kelly Miller.

Swin Cash had 16 points and eight rebounds for Detroit, and
Chandi Jones added career highs with 14 points and six assists.

The Fever built a double-figures lead in the first half with a
13-4 run to lead 32-21, and Detroit never drew closer than eight
points thereafter. A 3-pointer by Catchings ignited the run, giving
Indiana a 22-17 advantage with just under nine minutes left in the
first half.

Indiana took its biggest lead of the opening half at 41-27 on
two free throws by Stephanie White, held a 42-29 advantage at the
break and went on to lead by as many as 22 points in the second
half.

Catchings, Miller and White hit 3-pointers to open the second
half as the Fever marched to a 55-33 advantage. Detroit managed to
pull to within 11 points in the final two minutes, but the
defending WNBA champion dropped its third consecutive game.
